text:
every morning i wake up to fight a war,
wishing to have a life different from this and far.

going to work is not less than entering a battle ground,
the only difference is here am all alone with perverts all around.

everytime i excel in my work, i get an unwanted pat,
several eyes stay glued on me everytime i stand or sat.

i stopped using lift not getting health consious,
but trying to avoid even in that few minutes some unwanted nuisance.

everytime i sip, or anytime i trip,
people send creepy stares towards my lip or hip.

i wanted to work to achieve something,
but here i find them treating like an entertainment thing.

meet me in my cabin, everytime my boss says,
i get to misbehave he found some more new ways.

i am not dumb to say mum and shout out,
but what's the use, when with power and money, they harmlessly walk out

when i defend am not of that type and i have a family to take care and look,
everytime my responsibilties and duties, as my weakness and helplessness they mistook.

now am done with all this and lost my patience too,
and ready to raise voice against all this joining #metoo

#english #englishwriting
#writersofinstagram
#writershub #poetry
#metoo #harrasment #instawriters #instapoets
#lostgirl_from_heartstrings

wake up to that.  #metoo #resistpatriarchy #feministasfuck #freeyourself

text:
â€¢subway feet â€¢
â€œi was on the q train heading uptown after a long day in new york. i was listening to an entrepreneurial podcast with one earphone out just for safety reasons. when this man across from me hollers at me. he said â€œnice bootsâ€ i loved these boots they were black and made me feel confident until this moment. i ignored him, which only made him louder. he then says â€œ i bet you have cute feet in dem bootsâ€ i tried to keep my cool but it was torture. i felt trapped because i didnâ€™t want to give him any satisfaction by reacting to his words. he continues â€œ i bet you have sweet popsicle toes deep in dem boots, can i see em!â€ â€œ show me them feetâ€ at this point i felt helpless part of me wanted to exit right then. he then thought the man next me was my boyfriend, he was a stranger. the man asked him â€œis your girlfriends feet sexy? do you lick em, have her show me them.â€ the man replied with a laugh â€œ ha no man sorryâ€ no defense no help. 
i was truly disgusted and felt ashamed that not one person on that crowded car came to my defense what kind of person treats someone like this.â€ - anonymous

text:
let's be honest, i don't have it all together. 
my house is a mess. 
washing my hair makes me run late. 
then i can only find one shoe. 
and i get to work to realize my email hasn't been working for at least two days ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ one of those mornings that makes you want to go back home and start over. 
but instead i chugged my superfoods and called it. 
just take the next step.
just do the next thing. 
because there will always be obstacles. 
time will be limited. 
work will be crazy. 
your commitments keep you running. 
but if you want something different, just do the next thing. 
there would have been a time when i would have let these irritations ruin my day. 
that was before i found a tribe of women who made me see that life could be different. 
and when you're rocking #hotmess status, there's always someone there who can say #metoo, but let's do it anyway.
i'll do it with you. 
you don't have to do this journey alone. 
we're busy professionals. 
breastfeeding mamas. 
working moms. 
college students. 
healthcare professionals. 
teachers. 
and some days, we're hot messes. 
and there's room for you in this tribe.
there's no judgement here.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

the guardian

jon sharman
the independent

text:
my friend, the talented @joemartinez, is working on a complex collection of stories and images from people of mixed descent (which, really, is all of us) who have had a hard time fitting in fully to one world. whether it is racial difference or a displacement from one community to the next, people tend to simply not be able to label them very accurately. this leads to lots of assumptions about them that arenâ€™t true, and plenty of puzzled looks from people who are surprised in some way by how the way we imposters look doesnâ€™t mesh with who we are expected to be. but most of all, the project also explores your own question of identity - and how you inevitably make peace with who you are, no matter what people think of you.
.
i was honored to be a part of the series. and i donâ€™t look very much like the sleep-deprived science mum i am due to, in large effect, joeâ€™s mad skills at light placement and photography. or maybe, just telling him my imposter stories lifted such a weight off my chest that i look free.
.
thanks @joemartinez! #imposter #race #photography #socialexperiment #nolabels #womeninscience #feminist #survivor #metoo #phdmama #ivfbabies #doisurpriseyou ?

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

media reporting on issues of sexual violence is often under-informed and defends public myths and misconceptions about the dynamics of sexual violence. this misinformation affects societyâ€™s shared understanding of and attitudes to sexual violence, promoting rape culture.
â™¡
in new zealand, one in three girls will be subject to an unwanted sexual experience by the age of 16 years. 1 in 5 women will experience sexual assault as an adult.
â™¡
it is estimated that 90% of sexual violence is committed by someone known to the victim/survivor. for maori girls and women the likelihood of sexual violence is nearly twice as high as the general population. ğŸŒ¼
between 2004 to around 2007, between the ages of 4 and about 7, i was sexually abused by someone i knew. on the 16th of july 2018 i took him to court and there was no conviction. no punishment, no justice.

i am not a victim. i am a survivor.

frida kahlo said "pinto flores asi no mueren" i paint flowers so they will not die ğŸŒ± ğŸŒ¼
others will complain because to them we are thorn bushes, but those who love us rejoice because they know we are really just rose bushes with thorns! despite everythin we must start each day grateful for the love that supports us because even with all the capabilities within us, that is what gets us through.
ğŸŒ¹
we can keep fatally wondering 'why?' or we can see all this pain, heartbreak, injustice, as an opportunity to become our true selves. emerge from the concealed depths, into the gleaming luminescence! because the dealer the mud it grows in, the more beautiful the lotus that blooms. ğŸŒ·
if we always strive to look on the bright side, find the positive and keep our faces to the sun as the sunflower does, the dark and the shadows will fall behind us. and with the sun in our faces, we have the courage to move forward in the light of the day. ğŸŒ»

i paint flowers so they will never ever die!

text:
did you know that telling a colleague that you're in love with them doesn't necessarily constitute sexual harassment? 
link in bio
clip: https://youtu.be/wuj87piogry
full webinar: https://youtu.be/mimsc050-oq

transcript (of clip): question: 
an employee in a completely different department who had said to the colleague that he was in love with her. he quit as soon as he told her. would that be considered sexual harassment?

allegra fishel:
(gender equality law, founder and executive director)
i think a one-time expression of caring for someone else is probably more likely than not--not sexual harassment. you have to look at the whole factual scenario: see if there's previous conduct.

maya raghu:
(national womenâ€™s law center, director of workplace equality and senior counsel)
were those people friends before or is this something where they were sort of strangers, and this guy became obsessed with her and started telling her that he loved her?

allegra fishel:
has he said he has loved her multiple times, and she said please don't say this? but a one-time expression? i would not say that that's sexual harassment.

full webinar: https://youtu.be/wuj87piogry

description of full webinar: https://www.youngfeministsnow.com/events/2018/10/21

confused about what constitutes sexual harassment and what doesnâ€™t? do you want to do the right thing, but unsure of how to proceed? are you wondering if the #metoo movement means that any romantic relationship at work is automatically considered sexual harassment?

during this webinar, national experts explain the nuances of sexual harassment in layman terms.

attorneys and advocates also describe tools and tips to create harassment-free cultures in diverse settings.
---what are the additional considerations when the victim is a woman of color or gender nonconforming?
---what if the victim is undocumented?

learn how to go beyond legal requirements to create cultures where every employee is treated with respect, and therefore better performing. q&a afterward.  #metoo #timesup #feminism #feminist #undocumented #immigration #rapeculture #sexualassault #titleix #woc #diverse #diversity #sexualharassment

.

.
.
 i have discovered, through this long process, the bad days are slowly being outweighed by good days.... the days when i can be honest with myself about how iâ€™m feeling, and still show up for myself and the people i love. .
and thatâ€™s all i can ask for.

text:
please share and read as many of you know, there were several articles in the news about neal and his sexual abuse. in the espn article, gary ream stated that he was putting neal on leave. ironically, gary ream is one of nealâ€™s close friends and one of the people that tried to intimidate me to keep silent. 
shame on you gary ream! 
gary knew about this abuse long before it was reported to safesport, yet he did nothing. under safesport rules, gary was supposed to report the allegations within 1 day. he never did. instead of putting the interest of young female skateboarders first, gary ream decided to protect his own interest and tried to prevent any bad press that would negatively affect his standing within the olympic movement.  i was told gary ream hired tim curley who was convicted and went to jail for covering up the penn state sexual abuse of young boys by jerry sandusky, is this the guy that will protect the abused or the abuser? 
shame on you gary ream! 
young girls in skateboarding remain susceptible to sexual predators because of people like gary ream, who brush negative press under the rug to protect themselves. garyâ€™s leadership provides protection for sexual predators and promotes the sexual victimization of girls.  neal hendrix shouldnâ€™t be put on leave, he should be put in jail and men like gary ream should be stripped of the power that they failed to exercise.  instead of trying to silence girls who speak up, skateboarding should have leaders that protect all the athletes and give everyone a fair shot. it is people like neal hendrix and gary ream who turn the olympic movement into a toxic environment for women. 
i have taken back my power by exposing these people for who they are. i hope the international olympic committee and its affiliates will demonstrate the courage to exercise their power and safeguard young female athletes by permanently eliminating sexual predators and the men like gary ream who protect them. 
thank you for listening... god bless  #metoo #metooskateboarding #sexualabusesurvivor
#whyididntreport
#iamnotafraidtosayit #iamnotafraidanymore #ihavecontrol #sexualassaultisnotok || @taranajaneen

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn
